(35,2,1,'2014-03-12 12:18:12','Psyched','<p>Yesterday (in-between job hunting) I updated the <a href=\"http://psychedharma.com\">psychedharma.com</a> website with an \"elib-blog\" integration that seemed to go pretty smoothly. The software depends on \"elib-base\" and <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">Empathy</a> and these are the same three main components that this site also depends on (as well as the templating library Smarty). The three components can now all be installed using Composer however elib-blog is not currently a stable enough project to be public. I have also been working towards a new release of Empathy (version 0.9.6) which will include updated documentation. All information regarding this micro-framework is gradually starting to be stockpiled over at <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">empathyphp.co.uk</a>. (Notice the attempt at making the project look as official as possible.) Be warned that finalising the next release is still in progress and the same is true for the accompanying docs.</p>\r\n<p>Attempting to see things as objectively as possible, I\'m pretty pleased that setting up a new blog using this stack of easily installable components went so well and I can\'t help but wonder how long it would have taken me to put together something similar using Wordpress and be as happy with the overall result - even though I admit that what I was looking for was ultimately quite minimal in terms of features. The main things I cared about implementing were multiple categories, a blog archive widget, responsive layout (that still needs some improvement), SEO friendly URLs, RSS feed, site SEO settings, caching mechanism and of course a simple secured admin area for managing blog posts themselves. Eventually I began to start to feel freed up to start planning some really killer features (jokes) like a cartoon cat that will pop up and say random things to site visitors. I guess that\'s a sign that things went pretty a-ok in the end.</p>','psyched'),
(36,1,1,'2014-03-12 13:18:54','Reading material','<p>If buying books like this doesn\'t prove my love of Open Source, I\'m not sure what will. &nbsp;Unless it would feel more comfortable for you to imagine it\'s some kind fan-fiction hardback novel set in the Star Wars universe.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','debian'),
(37,2,1,'2014-05-14 20:33:12','Vagrant Debian Box','<p>Today I couldn\'t get synced (shared) folders working first time around with Vagrant and VirtualBox, which led me to creating my first Vagrant \"box\" AKA &nbsp;base system virtual machine image based upon a VirtualBox instance.</p>\r\n<p>After spending ages on a wild goose chase because I thought the issue was due to a mis-match in the VirtualBox guest additions version compared to the version of the VirtualBox client, I eventually reaslised that all I needed to do was reinstall the package \'virtualbox-guest-utils\' in order to run mount with \"vboxsf\" as a recognised filesystem.</p>\r\n<p>Another brilliant tip came from the \"Vagrant: Up and Running\" book by Mitchell Hashimoto (as opposed to Google) for reducing the finished packaged box file size, ready for redistribution. &nbsp;Runnning the following command effectively defragments the virtual disk image, ready for optimised compression. Handy!</p>\r\n<pre>$ dd if=/dev/zero of=/EMPTY bs=1M\r\n$ rm -f /EMPTY</pre>\r\n<p>Update: 19/05/2014. &nbsp;I was getting some issues with \"stdin: is not a tty\" errors while provisioning using the shelll, which was leading to other problems when attempting to solve it by using \"config.ssh.pty = true\". I finally found the real solution from <a href=\"http://tech.karbassi.com/2011/11/09/stdin-is-not-a-tty/\">http://tech.karbassi.com/2011/11/09/stdin-is-not-a-tty/</a> which needed applying to the default /root/.profile file.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','boxes'),
(38,2,1,'2014-09-04 01:46:05','dignan porch great escape','<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTYsImJsb2dfaWQiOjM4LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6IlVudGl0bGVkLTEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>','dignan'),
(39,3,1,'2015-04-07 00:44:25','Real Fears','<p>Today I realised something pretty insanely important. I feel like I&rsquo;ve always known, growing up, that my main problem/challenge/struggle/issue/difficulty (whatever you want to call it) in life has been coping with a core belief in me from when I was a child that has lead to a &ldquo;fear of abandonment&rdquo;. Unfortunately I must accept this is going to be a life-long struggle to cope with. Just like other more physical or physiological problems.</p>\r\n<p>Apart from never really understanding the issue very well - not well enough to accept that it may be genuine phobia of mine. The really troubling aspect to this problem is that, call me a cop-out if you want but it seems to me if you have this issue then you are most likely to be going to be attacked because of it from those who are responsible for imparting it on you.</p>\r\n<p>Today after about ten minutes of quick Duck-Duck-Going (Googling) I found myself suddenly quite shocked to find that it is apparently a condition that, first of all, isn&rsquo;t that uncommon. So much so that some believe it is an issue that is potentially wired into our collective subconscious as humans via mythology.</p>\r\n<p>More interesting and perhaps believable was finding that it is clearly considered a genuine phobia for sufferers and more interesting still was getting a quick sense of what the standard treatments for it might involve. It wasn&rsquo;t a shock to learn that some standard cognitive therapy type treatments out there may exist that probably aim to help people recognise the negative thought patterns that can exist within, so that they may be recognised, dealt with, challenged or easily dismissed by the individual as an ongoing process of a CBT-style &lsquo;becoming one&rsquo;s own doctor&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p>What is most profound to me is learning that it is completely recognised that people who suffer from this phobia often grow up with feelings of not belonging to a group or a &lsquo;pack&rsquo; and that the recommended way of dealing with that is by spending time analysing one&rsquo;s own passions and dreams in life and then making it an ongoing mission to find people who share these and therefore find people to be surrounded by who can directly or indirectly provide support for the individual.</p>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s pretty amazing to me when I think about this because similar to other treatments I&rsquo;ve ended up finding relief from in life, this kind of recommended process of &ldquo;tribe-finding&rdquo; is something that I&rsquo;ve definitely tried to explore since I was a teenager, perhaps knowing intuitively that it must be the antidote required for a happier life. It does make me wonder though Nick Hornby style: &ldquo;Am I sad because I listen to pop music or do I listen to pop music because I&rsquo;m sad.&rdquo; As in do I love the things in life that I do because I just do or because I figured the people who do those things would make a cool crew to hang out with and therefore will not have to face being alone. (Cries.)</p>\r\n<p>Wait that&rsquo;s getting a bit meta. Let&rsquo;s just assume that my passions in life are genuine and normal. After all photography experts weren&rsquo;t that cool when I was a teenager. They were just grey haired men who hung out in dark rooms.</p>\r\n<p>When it comes to music though, which is a bigger passion now, what other sense of belonging can possibly exist for a person than being in a band and maybe being lucky enough to go on the road and travel and really live the ultimate pack-like fantasies? I suppose it shouldn&rsquo;t come as a surprise to me when I think of of how much of a relief it was when I was eighteen and finally started doing music more seriously. Although that may have been because I also found people I could do music with who definitely shared my world-view and who were also my family as a massive added bonus. (Big families are awesome). I&rsquo;ve often found myself joking to people who ask me about my musical exploits that the basic need for it comes from the innate ability a band can provide in free group therapy from within a surrogate dysfunctional family setting. Aside from all that creative razzamatazz.</p>\r\n<p>What I am learning now - still the hard way it seems - is how super easily this ugly fear that resides in me can rear it&rsquo;s head when I&rsquo;m feeling only moderately insecure. But most crucially though is realising that I am equally prone to falling into the worst of these imaginary abandonment traps when the relationship(s) in question that I am fearful of losing are professional ones.</p>\r\n<p>This is pretty big deal as realisations go and I am feeling super lucky right know to have finally put these missing pieces of the jigsaw together. How else can things routinely go so wrong for a person when I have been lucky enough to intuitively reach out and try and join a pack of humans because I love what they do - but can also provide me with a career. I have been so lucky in having some extremely supportive people as my superiors over the years and even more amazing is considering that some of these have come along while working on a contract/freelancer basis.</p>\r\n<p>Maybe now, with this in mind, I can finally start to realise that it cannot simply be success alone or achieving things that I am afraid of. It all boils down to the relationships that are part and parcel of that struggle.</p>\r\n<p>These days computer geeks can&rsquo;t seem to get enough of spending time with each other as separate inner tribes and crazily you could argue that the outcome of these tribal communities has a direct correlation to the content of the training programs of most IT recruiters and the distillation of which probably leads to the buzzword frenzied modus operandi of the whole industry maybe even cyclically both industries. Recruiters though are people, I&rsquo;m learning, are some of the most important people that I need to relate to on Earth. If only one of them would take me seriously when I say that I am drawn to technologies often simply because of the communities behind them and not just because of the technology itself.</p>','fears'),
(40,2,1,'2015-05-15 13:39:06','Brief Intro to GPG','<p><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/dvt6ITiRsSs\" width=\"100%\" height=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe></p>\r\n<p>I wanted to challenge myself to produce a quick lightening talk style / screen capture walkthrough video demonstrating the simple use of GPG at a high level.</p>\r\n<p>I guess it was a bit of a must-have topic for a nerdy fellow, such as myself starting out with being on youtube as an open geek. &nbsp;I am by no means an expert of encryption/cryptography but I suppose I feel pretty passiontely about these tools staying freely available and hopefully &nbsp;better understood by \"the average Internet user\". I am super welcoming of any feedback.. you never know, if I can build on the confidence gained from these inital videos maybe one day I\'ll be ready to talk about my own code and coding experiences during a real lighting talk (somewhere suitable).<br /><br />Enjoy.</p>','gpg'),
(41,2,1,'2015-07-09 11:29:00','torred users','<p>I became curious, today, thinking about what it might take to create a website that had a simple mechanism that could offer all of it\'s users the assurance of protected anonymity.</p>\r\n<p>I had a hunch that some kind of public API/service might exist for looking up Tor exit nodes based on IP address and lo and behold I found out about the <a href=\"https://www.torproject.org/projects/tordnsel.html.en\">TorDNSEL</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Translating this into a chunk of PHP code that could be feasibly inserted into evey PHP script on a server, I came up with this:</p>\r\n<pre>&lt;?php\r\n$output = array();\r\nexec(\'dig \'.implode(\'.\', array_reverse(explode(\'.\', $_SERVER[\'REMOTE_ADDR\']))).\'.6667.4.3.2.1.ip-port.exitlist.torproject.org\', $output);\r\n$torred = preg_match(\'/127\\.0\\.0\\.2/\', implode(\'\', $output));\r\nif (!$torred) {\r\n    $greeting = \'user we can track\';\r\n} else {\r\n    $greeting = \'secret anonymous Internet user\';\r\n} ?&gt;\r\nhello, &lt;?php echo $greeting; ?&gt;.\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>In terms of doing something more substantial with it, I would use this code directly after initiating a user\'s session, where I would check the existence of a stored \'torred\' flag or otherwise call the check and, if it fails, redirect the user to a polite go-away page.</p>\r\n<p>For a demo visit this URL using a regular browser vs. using tor or a copy of TorBrowser:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ai-em.net/tor.php\">http://ai-em.net/tor.php</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Job done.</p>','torreduser'),
(42,1,1,'2015-07-15 04:26:46','Only wimps use tape backup','<p>Yes, this famous quote by Linux Torvalds. Or in it\'s entiretly:<br /><br /></p>\r\n<blockquote>&ldquo;Only wimps use tape backup. REAL men just upload their important stuff on ftp and let the rest of the world mirror it.&rdquo;<br /><br /></blockquote>\r\n<p>So I am officially putting the open source thing aside. Like drumming, I am coming to terms that it is a dying artform. &nbsp;Because drumming is apparently endangered and will only survive thanks to new gizmos being invented on Kickstarter.&nbsp;</p>','deathofthings'),
(43,2,1,'2015-07-22 12:56:03','Another week another PHP technical test','<p>Due to working on a test for a new potential role, I&rsquo;ve been made to take a slightly deeper look into using database calls with mysqli (the MySQL Improved extension).</p>\r\n<p>I admit that since acquiring an official fave object-relational-mapping tool for PHP - <a href=\"http://www.redbeanphp.com/\">Redbean</a> - I have stopped caring too much about lower level differences in PHP database abstractions libraries/extensions because Redbean like many others just uses PDO. I hadn&rsquo;t, for instance, realised that parameter binding is perfectly possible with PDO and has been for quite some time.</p>\r\n<p>When I first saw mysqli in action, this feature was apparently still quite new in PDO, which explains why I might have been persuaded that it wasn&rsquo;t supported at all. Since then it has stayed with me that, for this reason, mysqli is more secure (from SQL injection attacks) but now I realise the only difference seems to be that it can be slightly more performant than PDO as long as fully hard coding an application to just use MySQL as a database dependency is a-ok with you.</p>\r\n<p>So I&rsquo;ve ended up looking at mysqli prepared statements, keen to lay some groundwork, in order to have some code that I could potentially use as a proof of concept for showing that mysqli can outperform a very lightweight PDO active-record style and extreme legacy code ORM of mine. Of which I feel awkwardly proud to say hasn&rsquo;t changed much in almost ten years. Probably because even though crude, it has been at the heart of many projects, pretty much unchanged and therefore a beacon of my understanding of backwards compatibly issues that have affected the surrounding code it lives in.</p>\r\n<p>As soon as I got into parameter binding, I naturally wanted to create a little wrapper function for my querying (around mysqli procedural calls) and this led to the use of PHPs \"call_user_func\" callback method, &nbsp;so that I could send arbitrary length parameter lists. The documentation warns of potential difficulties with parameter binding as these are expected to be in the form of references. I didn&rsquo;t realise at first how much of a due warning was necessary. It turned out it was pretty justified. There is quite a lot of hits out there on the subject of references in php and particularly with foreach loops. i.e. when creating (and reusing) a loop like this:</p>\r\n<pre>foreach ($data as &amp;$item) {\r\n    // some stuff\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>Before I got to the conclusion provided by momslatin_dadsasian on the &lsquo;lolphp&rsquo; subreddit, which I am now newly acquainted with:</p>\r\n<blockquote>My general rule with foreach and references is: fuck php and use something else</blockquote>\r\n<p>I persevered believing that what I was trying to achieve MUST be possible. I won&rsquo;t try and explain the deal with references and foreach loops but in a nutshell it seems these references both exist outside of the foreach loop and also don&rsquo;t exist at the same time. Or another way of looking at it seems to be a reference will exist but only if you attempt to observe it and even then it will be in a slightly different place.</p>\r\n<p>Suffice to say I didn&rsquo;t feel like learning quantum theory in order to execute a pretty straightforward technical test for a part time web development job. So I quickly hacked together a different approach. So instead of this:</p>\r\n<pre>$refs = array();\r\nforeach ($foo as $bar){ \r\n    $refs[] =&amp; $bar;\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>I tried this and I was rewarded with the expected behaviour.</p>\r\n<pre>$refs = array();\r\nforeach ($foo as $index =&gt; $bar) {\r\n    $refs[] =&amp; $foo[$index];\r\n}\r\n</pre>','refhell'),
(44,1,1,'2015-09-28 06:34:43','Goodbye to Berlin','<p>aaa</p>','berlin'),
(45,1,1,'2015-11-04 02:24:09','Ssl in love with php','<p>As you may have noticed, I have made a lot of my code public recently. &nbsp;For good. Done. &nbsp;It\'s warts and all out there. &nbsp;The reasoning begging this is simply to get the most use out of the code that as far as I can tell wants to be free. &nbsp;This means I\'m automatically encouraged to think about making sensible releases (and branches) and also thanks to packagist, I never need to worry about using explicit repositories within composer. &nbsp;i am reaping the rewards of open source rven though I am the only person seemingly who cares. &nbsp;That seems to say a lot for the strength of standard tools and practices in the open source world.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>i can\'t sleep this evening because I am so excited about fixing a broken laptop with a new hard drive that could vibe one first Linux workstation in 7 years. and because I figured out a simple at to serve empathy apps over h without breaking the routing to local asset files and links. &nbsp;This will be achieved by making a new custom smarty plugin that dynamically finds and replaces on offending absolute urls that have the incorrect http prefix protocol. &nbsp;Not a solution that\'s going to increase performance but one that will just work. &nbsp;That\'s what I still love about php. &nbsp;if you make the effort you can create something robust that just works and will continue to do so nearly ten y down the line. &nbsp;Here\'s to another ten years!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Code snippet.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Newplugin'),
(46,2,1,'2014-11-08 23:00:14','I Hear a New World','<p>Photos from Vincent Larkin\'s event \"<a href=\"http://www.vam.ac.uk/whatson/event/3823/i-hear-a-new-world-performance-inspired-by-the-harry-hammond-ph-5361/\">I Hear a New World</a>\".&nbsp; Part of his residency&nbsp;at the V&amp;A and featuring the band Showman\'s Wagon.</p>\r\n<p>See more of Vincent\'s work at <a href=\"http://www.vincentlarkin.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">www.vincentlarkin.co.uk</a>.</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTA1LCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NiwiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJpbWFnZV8xXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTA4LCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NiwiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJpbWFnZV80XzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTE1LCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NiwiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJpbWFnZV8xMV8xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTE2LCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NiwiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJpbWFnZV8xMl8xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTE5LCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NiwiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJpbWFnZV8xNV8xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','ihearanewworld'),
(47,2,1,'2014-11-17 16:11:28','Joya 2nd behind the scenes photos','<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTYsImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZG9pZzVfMS5qcGciLCJpbWFnZV93aWR0aCI6bnVsbCwiaW1hZ2VfaGVpZ2h0IjpudWxsLCJzaXplIjoiIiwiZmx1aWQiOiJpbWctZmx1aWQiLCJjZW50ZXJlZCI6IiIsImNhcHRpb24iOiIifQ==]</p>\r\n<p>The new EP is out. Please go to the <a href=\"https://joya.bandcamp.com\">bandcamp link</a>&nbsp;to listen to it and buy!</p>\r\n<p>To celebrate this megastrophic event we (I, me, whoever) are excited to reveal an exclusive set of photos that visually represent some of the vibing goings-on, behind the scenes, of the EPs <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/no-recording-studio/97045361374\">No Recording Studio</a> session. &nbsp;Check it.</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTcsImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZGFuXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTgsImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZGVza18xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTksImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZG9pZ19qb2huXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTAwLCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX2RvaWcxXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTAxLCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX21hbmFraW5fMS5qcGciLCJpbWFnZV93aWR0aCI6bnVsbCwiaW1hZ2VfaGVpZ2h0IjpudWxsLCJzaXplIjoiIiwiZmx1aWQiOiJpbWctZmx1aWQiLCJjZW50ZXJlZCI6IiIsImNhcHRpb24iOiIifQ==]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTAyLCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX21pa2UxXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIj