(18,1,'<p>Step 1 - Install Symfony into your PHP library path:</p>\r\n<pre># cd /usr/share/php<br /># wget http://www.symfony-project.org/get/symfony-stable.tgz<br /># gunzip symfony-stable.tgz ; tar -xvf symfony-stable.tar<br /># ln -s symfony-X/lib symfony<br /># mkdir data<br /># ln -s ../symfony-X/data data/symfony<br /># rm syfony-stable.tar</pre>\r\n<p>Step 2 - Within your Symfony app, edit the main \'settings.yml\' file, create a symlink to \'sf\' and ensure the cache directory is writable:</p>\r\n<pre>$ cd /var/www/localhost/htdocs/sf_app<br />$ echo \"all:\" &gt;&gt; config/settings.yml<br />$ echo \"  .settings\" &gt;&gt; config/settings.yml<br />$ echo \"    relative_url_root: /sf_app/web\" &gt;&gt; config/settings.yml<br />$ ln -s /usr/share/php/data/symfony/web/sf .<br />$ chmod -R 777 cache</pre>\r\n<p>And you\'re done.</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"php\",\"lamp\",\"symfony\"],\"slug\":\"symfony\",\"heading\":\"Running a Symfony application from a directory\"}','2024-12-14 17:40:48'),
(19,2,'<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Welcome to my new personal website and blog.&nbsp; I\'m afraid I\'ve decided that it\'s going to be (almost) purely technical around here from now on. I\'m going to talk about what I do in terms of code and machines and hopefully get the chance to share some of things I\'ve figured out.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"general\",\"eatyourowndogfood\"],\"slug\":\"hi\",\"heading\":\"Welcome\"}','2024-12-14 17:41:08'),
(20,1,'<p>Step 1 - Install Symfony into your PHP library path:</p>\r\n<pre># cd /usr/share/php<br /># wget http://www.symfony-project.org/get/symfony-stable.tgz<br /># gunzip symfony-stable.tgz ; tar -xvf symfony-stable.tar<br /># ln -s symfony-X/lib symfony<br /># mkdir data<br /># ln -s ../symfony-X/data data/symfony<br /># rm syfony-stable.tar</pre>\r\n<p>Step 2 - Within your Symfony app, edit the main \'settings.yml\' file, create a symlink to \'sf\' and ensure the cache directory is writable:</p>\r\n<pre>$ cd /var/www/localhost/htdocs/sf_app<br />$ echo \"all:\" &gt;&gt; config/settings.yml<br />$ echo \"  .settings\" &gt;&gt; config/settings.yml<br />$ echo \"    relative_url_root: /sf_app/web\" &gt;&gt; config/settings.yml<br />$ ln -s /usr/share/php/data/symfony/web/sf .<br />$ chmod -R 777 cache</pre>\r\n<p>And you\'re done.</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"php\",\"lamp\",\"symfony\"],\"slug\":\"symfony\",\"heading\":\"Running a Symfony application from a directory\"}','2024-12-14 17:43:55'),
(21,47,'<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTYsImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZG9pZzVfMS5qcGciLCJpbWFnZV93aWR0aCI6bnVsbCwiaW1hZ2VfaGVpZ2h0IjpudWxsLCJzaXplIjoiIiwiZmx1aWQiOiJpbWctZmx1aWQiLCJjZW50ZXJlZCI6IiIsImNhcHRpb24iOiIifQ==]</p>\r\n<p>The new EP is out. Please go to the <a href=\"https://joya.bandcamp.com\">bandcamp link</a>&nbsp;to listen to it and buy!</p>\r\n<p>To celebrate this megastrophic event we (I, me, whoever) are excited to reveal an exclusive set of photos that visually represent some of the vibing goings-on, behind the scenes, of the EPs <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/no-recording-studio/97045361374\">No Recording Studio</a> session. &nbsp;Check it.</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTcsImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZGFuXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTgsImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZGVza18xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTksImJsb2dfaWQiOjQ3LCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6InBfZG9pZ19qb2huXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTAwLCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX2RvaWcxXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTAxLCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX21hbmFraW5fMS5qcGciLCJpbWFnZV93aWR0aCI6bnVsbCwiaW1hZ2VfaGVpZ2h0IjpudWxsLCJzaXplIjoiIiwiZmx1aWQiOiJpbWctZmx1aWQiLCJjZW50ZXJlZCI6IiIsImNhcHRpb24iOiIifQ==]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTAyLCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX21pa2UxXzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTAzLCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX21pa2U0XzEuanBnIiwiaW1hZ2Vfd2lkdGgiOm51bGwsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6bnVsbCwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiIn0=]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTA0LCJibG9nX2lkIjo0NywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJwX2piMl8xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>','{\"category\":[\"5\"],\"tags\":[\"joya\"],\"slug\":\"2ndphotos\",\"heading\":\"Joya 2nd behind the scenes photos\"}','2024-12-14 17:54:41'),
(22,61,'<p>I\'m working on a new blog.&nbsp; Bringing back to life some old content because, hey, dummy data is good but also for posterity I suppose!<br /><br /><br /></p>','{\"category\":[\"1\",\"3\"],\"tags\":[\"blog\",\"empathy\",\"remix\"],\"slug\":\"return\",\"heading\":\"New Blog\"}','2024-12-14 18:03:07'),
(23,50,'<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTIsImJsb2dfaWQiOjUwLCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6IkRTQ0YwODQyX18xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>I spent the afternoon with the two humans known as Sam McGarrigle and Ben Waggett (from Human Nature). I had driven us into to town because I was determined to get some small parts to fix up Ben\'s acoustic guitar and we ended up at Brighton marina where it turned into an opportune moment for a quick photo shoot using the camera that was paid for using Bitcoins. Here\'s to short excursions by the sea. For a moment it felt like a holiday.</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6ODUsImJsb2dfaWQiOjUwLCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6IkRTQ0YwODI5X18xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTAsImJsb2dfaWQiOjUwLCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6IkRTQ0YwODQwX18xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTEsImJsb2dfaWQiOjUwLCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6IkRTQ0YwODQxX18xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>\r\n<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6OTMsImJsb2dfaWQiOjUwLCJmaWxlbmFtZSI6IkRTQ0YwODQzX18xLmpwZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjpudWxsLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOm51bGwsInNpemUiOiIiLCJmbHVpZCI6ImltZy1mbHVpZCIsImNlbnRlcmVkIjoiIiwiY2FwdGlvbiI6IiJ9]</p>','{\"category\":[\"5\"],\"tags\":[\"humannature\",\"portraiture\"],\"slug\":\"behindthescenes\",\"heading\":\"Family Vibes\"}','2024-12-15 10:11:11'),
(24,40,'<p><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/dvt6ITiRsSs\" width=\"100%\" height=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe></p>\r\n<p>I wanted to challenge myself to produce a quick lightening talk style / screen capture walkthrough video demonstrating the simple use of GPG at a high level.</p>\r\n<p>I guess it was a bit of a must-have topic for a nerdy fellow, such as myself starting out with being on youtube as an open geek. &nbsp;I am by no means an expert of encryption/cryptography but I suppose I feel pretty passiontely about these tools staying freely available and hopefully &nbsp;better understood by \"the average Internet user\". I am super welcoming of any feedback.. you never know, if I can build on the confidence gained from these inital videos maybe one day I\'ll be ready to talk about my own code and coding experiences during a real lighting talk (somewhere suitable).<br /><br />Enjoy.</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"gpg\"],\"slug\":\"gpg\",\"heading\":\"Brief Intro to GPG\"}','2024-12-15 11:53:22'),
(25,35,'<p>Yesterday (in-between job hunting) I updated the <a href=\"http://psychedharma.com\">psychedharma.com</a>&nbsp;website with an \"elib-blog\" integration that seemed to go pretty smoothly. &nbsp; The software depends on \"elib-base\" and <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">Empathy</a>&nbsp;and these are the same three main components that this site also depends on (as well as the templating library Smarty). &nbsp;The three components can now all be installed using Composer however elib-blog is not currently a stable enough project to be public. &nbsp;I have also been working towards a new release of Empathy (version 0.9.6) &nbsp;which will include updated documentation. &nbsp;All information regarding this micro-framework is gradually starting to be stockpiled over at <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">empathyphp.co.uk</a>. (Notice the attempt at making the project look as official as possible.)&nbsp;&nbsp;Be warned that finalizing the next release is still in progress and the same is true for the accompanying docs.</p>\r\n<p>Attempting to see things as objectively as possible, I\'m pretty pleased that setting up a new blog using this stack of easily installable components went so well and I can\'t help but wonder how long it would have taken me to put together something similar using Wordpress and be as happy with the overall result - even though I admit that what I was looking for was ultimately quite minimal in terms of features. &nbsp;The main things I cared about implementing were multiple categories, a blog archive widget, responsive layout (that still needs some improvement), SEO friendly URLs, RSS feed, site SEO settings, caching mechanism and of course a simple secured admin area for managing blog posts themselves. &nbsp;Eventually I began to start to feel freed up to start planning some really killer features (jokes) like a cartoon cat that will pop up and say random things to site visitors. &nbsp;I guess that\'s a sign that things went pretty a-ok in the end.</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"empathy\",\"blogging\"],\"slug\":\"psyched\",\"heading\":\"Psyched\"}','2024-12-15 11:55:42'),
(26,49,'<p>The band Human Nature, originally from West Sussex, will be hitting up a close circle of friends in south London this time next week with their premiere live performance and we can\'t help ourselves but be rooting and tooting over this imminent epochal moment. &nbsp;Here are some quick shots of the band and a quick promo video we threw together based on some rehearsal vibes that went down a couple of weeks ago, just as we entered the new year, from the band\'s newly established fucking sweet jam zone.</p>\r\n<p>Look out for more from these guys soon.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"embed-responsive embed-responsive-16by9\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/t1XxeS-wVFA\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe></p>\r\n<p class=\"embed-responsive embed-responsive-16by9\">Euan, Del, Tom and Ben AKA Human Nature.</p>\r\n<p><img id=\"blog_image_67\" class=\"center img-responsive\" src=\"/tt/tt.php?src=./uploads/hnposter.jpg&amp;w=940&amp;h=\" alt=\"\" /></p>','{\"category\":[\"2\"],\"tags\":[\"humannature\"],\"slug\":\"humannature\",\"heading\":\"Human Nature\"}','2024-12-15 12:16:20'),
(27,35,'<p>hello, world</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"empathy\",\"blogging\"],\"slug\":\"psyched\",\"heading\":\"Psyched\"}','2024-12-15 12:22:19'),
(28,35,'<p>Yesterday (in-between job hunting) I updated the <a href=\"http://psychedharma.com\">psychedharma.com</a> website with an \"elib-blog\" integration that seemed to go pretty smoothly. The software depends on \"elib-base\" and <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">Empathy</a> and these are the same three main components that this site also depends on (as well as the templating library Smarty). The three components can now all be installed using Composer however elib-blog is not currently a stable enough project to be public. I have also been working towards a new release of Empathy (version 0.9.6) which will include updated documentation. All information regarding this micro-framework is gradually starting to be stockpiled over at <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">empathyphp.co.uk</a>. (Notice the attempt at making the project look as official as possible.) Be warned that finalising the next release is still in progress and the same is true for the accompanying docs.</p>\r\n<p>Attempting to see things as objectively as possible, I\'m pretty pleased that setting up a new blog using this stack of easily installable components went so well and I can\'t help but wonder how long it would have taken me to put together something similar using Wordpress and be as happy with the overall result - even though I admit that what I was looking for was ultimately quite minimal in terms of features. The main things I cared about implementing were multiple categories, a blog archive widget, responsive layout (that still needs some improvement), SEO friendly URLs, RSS feed, site SEO settings, caching mechanism and of course a simple secured admin area for managing blog posts themselves. Eventually I began to start to feel freed up to start planning some really killer features (jokes) like a cartoon cat that will pop up and say random things to site visitors. I guess that\'s a sign that things went pretty a-ok in the end.</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"empathy\",\"blogging\"],\"slug\":\"psyched\",\"heading\":\"Psyched\"}','2024-12-15 12:24:03'),
(29,35,'<p>Yesterday (in-between job hunting) I updated the <a href=\"http://psychedharma.com\">psychedharma.com</a> website with an \"elib-blog\" integration that seemed to go pretty smoothly. The software depends on \"elib-base\" and <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">Empathy</a> and these are the same three main components that this site also depends on (as well as the templating library Smarty). The three components can now all be installed using Composer however elib-blog is not currently a stable enough project to be public. I have also been working towards a new release of Empathy (version 0.9.6) which will include updated documentation. All information regarding this micro-framework is gradually starting to be stockpiled over at <a href=\"http://empathyphp.co.uk\">empathyphp.co.uk</a>. (Notice the attempt at making the project look as official as possible.) Be warned that finalising the next release is still in progress and the same is true for the accompanying docs.</p>\r\n<p>Attempting to see things as objectively as possible, I\'m pretty pleased that setting up a new blog using this stack of easily installable components went so well and I can\'t help but wonder how long it would have taken me to put together something similar using Wordpress and be as happy with the overall result - even though I admit that what I was looking for was ultimately quite minimal in terms of features. The main things I cared about implementing were multiple categories, a blog archive widget, responsive layout (that still needs some improvement), SEO friendly URLs, RSS feed, site SEO settings, caching mechanism and of course a simple secured admin area for managing blog posts themselves. Eventually I began to start to feel freed up to start planning some really killer features (jokes) like a cartoon cat that will pop up and say random things to site visitors. I guess that\'s a sign that things went pretty a-ok in the end.</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"empathy\",\"blogging\"],\"slug\":\"psyched\",\"heading\":\"Psyched\"}','2024-12-15 12:29:27'),
(30,12,'<p>It\'s been a long time since I figured this out and I can\'t remember what resource I used to help me. Anyway to get PHP Mode working with the native emacs bundled with Mac OS X do the following:</p>\r\n<pre>$ mkdir elisp; cd elisp\r\n$ wget http://bit.ly/cLqD47\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>Then edit/create the file \'~/.emacs and put in the following:</p>\r\n<pre>(add-to-list \'load-path \"~/elisp\")\r\n(load \"php-mode\")\r\n(add-to-list \'auto-mode-alist\r\n	     \'(\"\\\\.php[34]?\\\\\'\\\\|\\\\.phtml\\\\\'\" . php-mode))\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>Et voila, you will now have lovely syntax highlighting and auto indenting when editing your PHP files. (NB: The bit.ly link points to the php-mode.el script hosted on Sourceforge.)</p>','{\"category\":[\"1\"],\"tags\":[\"php\",\"emacs\",\"mac\"],\"slug\":\"emacs\",\"heading\":\"PHP Mode for emacs on Mac OS X\"}','2024-12-15 12:31:58'),
(31,62,'<p><a href=\"https://www.google.com\">Google</a></p>','{\"category\":[\"3\"],\"tags\":[\"google\"],\"slug\":\"google\",\"heading\":\"Test\"}','2024-12-15 12:51:31'),
(32,63,'<p><img class=\"img-fluid\" src=\"//blog.mikejw.co.uk/uploads/IMG_6735.jpeg\" alt=\"Self-hosting!\" data-payload=\"eyJpZCI6OCwiYmxvZ19pZCI6MTYsImZpbGVuYW1lIjoiSU1HXzY3MzUuanBlZyIsImltYWdlX3dpZHRoIjoiMjAxNiIsImltYWdlX2hlaWdodCI6IjE1MTIiLCJzaXplIjoiIiwiZmx1aWQiOiJpbWctZmx1aWQiLCJjZW50ZXJlZCI6IiIsImNhcHRpb24iOiJTZWxmLWhvc3RpbmchIn0=\" data-title=\"Self-hosting!\"></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Welcome to my new blog.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><br>I am a seasoned fullstack web developer who has specialised in front-end and React for the last 7-8 years.</p>\r\n<p>This blog application codebase is available at <a href=\"https://github.com/mikejw/blog\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">github.com/mikejw/blog</a> and is in fact code that can be generated using a \"bdcli quickstart\" command using my open source platform as a service and PHP MVC project found at <a href=\"https://empathy.sh\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">empathy.sh</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The documentation available for this project on the website is due for a wide overhall but, in essence, the command line tool \"bdcli\" now constitutes the DX component of the project which drives a Ansible/Docker functionality within another repo, \"base-docker\".&nbsp; &nbsp;It is no longer necessary to ever run an Ansible playbook manually from base-docker.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>bdcli and base-docker work in tandem to produce development environments for fullstack applications and can currently also be used to deploy a test/build server with Jenkins, using a web-facing proxy that can connect to the build/test server locally using Tailscale.&nbsp; There is additional code within \"base-docker\" for spinning up Vagrant VMs.&nbsp; These can be used as a standalone dev environment solution where there are two VMs, (a \'control\' VM and a \'node\' VM) and also a VM for the build/test server where it can run on a host machine instead being deployed in a dedicated fashion, for example (as more recently tested) on a Raspberry Pi.&nbsp; NB: when using the Vagrant VM development envrionment approach, bdcli is automatically installed.&nbsp; Simplifying the DX even more. i.e. This is the workflow for getting started using Empathy on a Windows host assuming Virtualbox, Vagrant and git bash have been installed (aside from ensuring some /etc/hosts file entires have been added):</p>\r\n<pre><code>\r\nvagrant up\r\nvagrant ssh control\r\nbdcli --version\r\nbdcli --help\r\nbdcli init --dev\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>To be perfectly honest I\'m at a bit of an impasse currently because although things regarding my open source project are gradually coallescing around bdcli and base docker to provide a simple, single interface to all functinality which can be setup using the simple approach above, to really get the most out it, if you are using a mac or Linux, then the better option is to ensure the machine has Ansible and Docker installed natively, bypassing any reliance on Vagrant/Virtualbox but convincing anyone to perform these steps is hard regardless of how easily this can be done using homebrew on mac, for example.<br><br>I am desparate for anyone who wants to try using Empathy to see if they can generate, modify and run projects (locally) and even better if they would be interersted in deploying them to a test server, which can make those projects accessible from the web within minutes (aside from some minimal infrastructural setup - i.e. Cloudflare, AWS, tailscale).&nbsp; Although the latest version of Empathy has been tested to (mostly) work without a glitch from inside Vagrant (i.e. when on Windows), this is only covering the latest stable features and not the test/build server insfrastucutre management and deployments from bdcli.</p>\r\n<p>Once I have found people who want to try these workflows and feedback to me the friction they might find I\'m not sure I can effectivey ensure the documentation has been updated sufficiently for the features that Empathy is close to offering that I\'m not aware of in any other project in a unified way.</p>','{\"category\":[\"3\"],\"tags\":[\"blog\",\"raspberrypi\",\"empathy\"],\"slug\":\"welcome\",\"heading\":\"Dog Food Fan\"}','2025-12-06 06:15:00'),
(33,63,'<p>[blog-image:eyJpZCI6MTIxLCJibG9nX2lkIjo2MywiZmlsZW5hbWUiOiJJTUdfNjczNV8xLmpwZWciLCJpbWFnZV93aWR0aCI6IjIwMTYiLCJpbWFnZV9oZWlnaHQiOiIxNTEyIiwic2l6ZSI6IiIsImZsdWlkIjoiaW1nLWZsdWlkIiwiY2VudGVyZWQiOiIiLCJjYXB0aW9uIjoiU2VsZi1ob3N0aW5nISJ9]</p>\r\n<p>Welcome to my new blog.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><br>I am a seasoned fullstack web developer who has specialised in front-end and React for the last 7-8 years.</p>\r\n<p>This blog application codebase is available at <a href=\"https://github.com/mikejw/blog\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">github.com/mikejw/blog</a> and is in fact code that can be generated using a \"bdcli quickstart\" command using my open source platform as a service and PHP MVC project found at <a href=\"https://empathy.sh\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">empathy.sh</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The documentation available for this project on the website is due for a wide overhall but, in essence, the command line tool \"bdcli\" now constitutes the DX component of the project which drives a Ansible/Docker functionality within another repo, \"base-docker\".&nbsp; &nbsp;It is no longer necessary to ever run an Ansible playbook manually from base-docker.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>bdcli and base-docker work in tandem to produce development environments for fullstack applications and can currently also be used to deploy a test/build server with Jenkins, using a web-facing proxy that can connect to the build/test server locally using Tailscale.&nbsp; There is additional code within \"base-docker\" for spinning up Vagrant VMs.&nbsp; These can be used as a standalone dev environment solution where there are two VMs, (a \'control\' VM and a \'node\' VM) and also a VM for the build/test server where it can run on a host machine instead being deployed in a dedicated fashion, for example (as more recently tested) on a Raspberry Pi.&nbsp; NB: when using the Vagrant VM development envrionment approach, bdcli is automatically installed.&nbsp; Simplifying the DX even more. i.e. This is the workflow for getting started using Empathy on a Windows host assuming Virtualbox, Vagrant and git bash have been installed (aside from ensuring some /etc/hosts file entires have been added):</p>\r\n<pre><code>\r\nvagrant up\r\nvagrant ssh control\r\nbdcli --version\r\nbdcli --help\r\nbdcli init --dev\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n<p>To be perfectly honest I\'m at a bit of an impasse currently because although things regarding my open source project are gradually coallescing around bdcli and base docker to provide a simple, single interface to all functinality which can be setup using the simple approach above, to really get the most out it, if you are using a mac or Linux, then the better option is to ensure the machine has Ansible and Docker installed natively, bypassing any reliance on Vagrant/Virtualbox but convincing anyone to perform these steps is hard regardless of how easily this can be done using homebrew on mac, for example.<br><br>I am desparate for anyone who wants to try using Empathy to see if they can generate, modify and run projects (locally) and even better if they would be interersted in deploying them to a test server, which can make those projects accessible from the web within minutes (aside from some minimal infrastructural setup - i.e. Cloudflare, AWS, tailscale).&nbsp; Although the latest version of Empathy has been tested to (mostly) work without a glitch from inside Vagrant (i.e. when on Windows), this is only covering the latest stable features and not the test/build server insfrastucutre management and deployments from bdcli.</p>\r\n<p>Once I have found people who want to try these workflows and feedback to me the friction they might find I\'m not sure I can effectivey ensure the documentation has been updated sufficiently for the features that Empathy is close to offering that I\'m not aware of in any other project in a unified way.</p>','{\"category\":[\"3\"],\"tags\":[\"empathy\",\"blog\",\"raspberrypi\"],\"slug\":\"welcome\",\"heading\":\"Dog Food Fan\"}','2025-12-06 06:16:49');
